                            <comment id="12974577" author="knutanders" created="Thu, 23 Dec 2010 09:17:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The problem seems to be that AssertFailureTest installs its own security policy, but this policy doesn&apos;t grant any privileges to junit.jar. The attached patch copies the following from derby_test.policy into the custom policy files for AssertFailureTest:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;grant codeBase &quot;$&lt;/p&gt;
{derbyTesting.junit}
&lt;p&gt;&quot; {&lt;br/&gt;
    // This permission is needed when running the tests using ant 1.7&lt;br/&gt;
    permission java.io.FilePermission &quot;$&lt;/p&gt;
{user.dir}
&lt;p&gt;$&lt;/p&gt;
{/}
&lt;p&gt;*&quot;, &quot;write&quot;;&lt;br/&gt;
};&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This allows Ant&apos;s JUnit runner to write to junitvmwatcherXYZ.properties, and the test runs cleanly again.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
